Core Concept

A real-time platform that matches students with compatible study partners based on goals, subjects, and habits—then lets them instantly collaborate via video/audio.

🔑 Core Features
1. 👤 User Profiles (but lightweight)

Keep this fast—don’t turn it into a full social network.

Required fields:

Name (or username)
College / School
Major
Year (Freshman–Grad)
Courses / Subjects (tag-based)
Bio
Should show a similarity

2. 🤖 AI Matching System (your differentiator)

match people based on their profile

3. 🎥 Live Study Sessions (core experience)

Must-have:

Video + audio (WebRTC)
Text chat
“Mute / camera off” options
mute the other person option

4. 🔄 Matching Flow

User clicks “Start Studying”
Matching screen (like Omegle)
Match found → session starts

Show why they matched:

“You both are Computer Science juniors studying Data Structures”

5. 🧑‍🤝‍🧑 Friend System (Retention Engine)

can add a friend
chat between friends


Session UI layout:

Video grid (center)
Timer (top)
Chat (side panel)
Controls (bottom)
⚙️ Tech Stack (practical)
Frontend
React / Next.js
Tailwind CSS
WebRTC (for video)
Backend
Node.js + Express
WebSockets (real-time matching)
PostgreSQL (profiles)
AI Layer
Start simple:
Matching algorithm (custom logic)
Later:
Embeddings for similarity
Behavior-based recommendations
Infra
Firebase / Supabase (fast MVP)
Or:
AWS + WebRTC servers (TURN/STUN)
🚀 MVP Scope (what to build first)

If you try to build everything, you’ll never launch.

MVP should include:

Basic profiles
Subject-based matching
Video + audio
Timer
Simple rating system

That’s it.

💡 What Will Make or Break This
1. Match quality > everything

If users get bad partners → they leave instantly.

2. Speed

Match should take <5 seconds.

3. Safety

If it feels like Omegle chaos → it’s dead.

4. Niche first

Start with:

One school
Or one subject (e.g., CS students)
🔥 Expansion Ideas

Once it works:

AI study assistant in sessions
Auto-generated summaries
Group sessions (3–5 people)
Integration with Google Calendar
“Exam cram mode” (high demand periods)
⚠️ Honest Reality Check

This is a great idea, but:

The hardest part is not tech—it’s liquidity (enough users online at once)
Cold start problem is real

Solution:

Launch in a single college (like Penn State 👀)
Seed with real users (clubs, classes, Reddit)

